ull,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["[('F statistic', np.float64(1.1444079593563594)),\n"," ('p-value', np.float64(0.1108677095752728))]"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":62}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# let's plot the fitted values vs residuals\n","\n","sns.residplot(\n","    data=df_pred, x=\"Fitted Values\", y=\"Residuals\", color=\"red\", lowess=True\n",")\n","plt.xlabel(\"Fitted Values\")\n","plt.ylabel(\"Residuals\")\n","plt.title(\"Fitted vs Residual plot\")\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":480},"id":"mc8Agx7xBHeZ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1757833189846,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":493,"user":{"displayName":"Sonal Kamble","userId":"04763039735760707592"}},"outputId":"cd80e78f-910e-4b78-c3b8-e3c1f3c92c8f"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["*   *The above scatter plot shows the distribution of residuals (errors) vs fitted values (predicted values).*\n","*   *The linearity of the relationship and homoscadasticity are being met.*\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"9b1MB9tAC-2_"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Normality of Residuals (Q-Q Plot and Shapiro-Wilk Test)**"],"metadata":{"id":"gZhoPsg2GzKL"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["sns.histplot(data=df_pred, x=\"Residuals\", kde=True)\n","plt.title(\"Normality of residuals\")\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":480},"id":"gmjV_n9tBdXw","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1757833484090,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":578,"user":{"displayName":"Sonal Kamble","userId":"04763039735760707592"}},"outputId":"a6177f07-ca74-4873-9e5f-7c183b3d48d8"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pylab\n","import scipy.stats as stats\n","\n","stats.probplot(df_pred[\"Residuals\"], dist=\"norm\", plot=pylab)\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":480},"id":"OFvYqrGKClMc","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1757833498459,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1554,"user":{"displayName":"Sonal Kamble","userId":"04763039735760707592"}},"outputId":"63af91c5-4dff-4f04-e9c1-1ab19400232f"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# 3. Normality Test: Shapiro-Wilk Test\n","stat, p_value = stats.shapiro(df_pred[\"Residuals\"])\n","print(f\"Shapiro-Wilk Test: Test Statistic = {stat:.4f}, p-value = {p_value:.4f}\")\n","if p_value > 0.05:\n","    print(\"Residuals appear to be normally distributed.\\n\")\n","else:\n","    print(\"Residuals are not normally distributed.\\n\")"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"21KRuIFVCodN","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1757833664708,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":59,"user":{"displayName":"Sonal Kamble","userId":"04763039735760707592"}},"outputId":"22208aef-91bb-4423-839f-3c332210fcbd"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Shapiro-Wilk Test: Test Statistic = 0.9972, p-value = 0.2847\n","Residuals appear to be normally distributed.\n","\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["*   The Q-Q plot shows points following the diagonal red line quite closely. Shapiro-Wilk test results: statistic = 0.9972, p-value = 0.2847 Since p-value > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that residuals are normally distributed Both visual and statistical tests strongly support the normality assumption.\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"JumFD5CqIHEA"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations**"],"metadata":{"id":"SYsds5fZKZ6J"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The model performs well on both the train and the test set with minimal difference in performance metrics between train and test sets indicates that the model generalizes well and is not overfitting. The high 𝑅 2 R 2 and adjusted 𝑅 2 R 2 values suggest that the model explains a significant proportion of the variance in the target variable.\n","\n","\n","**Significant Predictors**\n","\n","\n","1.   **Visitors and Views_Trailer:**\n","\n","One of the strongest predictors are visitors and views_trailer. An increase in the number of unique visitors directly translates to more content views. This is a crucial finding that reinforces the importance of overall platform growth and user acquisition. Additionally, the positive coefficient for views_trailer suggests that promoting trailers effectively increases content views.\n","\n","*   Recommendation:\n","\n","Focus marketing efforts on channels that bring in new visitors. Create and aggressively promote high-quality, engaging trailers for new content. Consider running A/B tests on different trailer formats and placements to maximize their impact.\n","\n","2.   **Day of the week:**\n","\n","Viewership is significantly higher on Saturdays, Sundays, and Wednesdays compared to the baseline day. These are peak viewing days for the platform.\n","\n","Recommendation:\n","\n","*   Strategic Scheduling: Schedule content releases, special events, and major promotional campaigns on these days to maximize initial viewership.\n","*   Audience Analysis: Analyze what types of content perform best on each of these days to inform future content acquisition and production decisions.\n","\n","3.   **Season:**\n","\n","All three seasonal variables (season_Spring, season_Summer, and season_Winter) have a positive impact on content views. This highlights that seasonality is a key factor influencing viewership. While the provided image doesn't include p-values, the magnitude of the coefficients suggests that these effects are likely statistically significant, as seen in the previously provided full regression table.\n","\n","Recommendations:\n","\n","\n","*   Prioritize Summer Content: Launch your most anticipated and high-budget content during the summer to take advantage of peak viewership. Focus marketing campaigns for major titles during this season to maximize their reach and impact.\n","*   Adjust Marketing Spend Seasonally: Allocate more of your marketing budget to summer, spring, and winter, as the return on investment for advertising and promotional activities is likely higher during these seasons due to increased user activity.\n","\n","\n","**less significant Predictors:**\n","\n","1.   **Ad_impressions:**\n","\n","The coefficient is positive but not statistically significant. This means there is no strong evidence that an increase in ad_impressions has a significant impact on content views, either positively or negatively.\n","\n","Recommendation:\n","\n","*   Focus the ad strategy on maximizing revenue per impression rather than using it as a tool to drive viewership.\n","*   Prioritize well-targeted ad campaigns with high visibility to ensure new content reaches the maximum audience. Focus on optimizing ad spend to maximize returns.\n","\n","2. **Genre:**\n","\n","The model shows that genre_Sci-Fi and genre_Thriller have positive coefficients, but they are not statistically significant. This means there's no strong evidence that these genres alone drive viewership\n","\n","Recommendation:\n","\n","*   Diversify Strategy: Avoid relying on genre as the sole driver for content acquisition. Focus instead on other factors that have a proven impact, such as high production quality, unique storytelling, and effective marketing.\n","\n","*   Refine Genre Definitions: It's possible that the current genre definitions are too broad. Consider a more granular analysis of sub-genres or specific content types within each genre to see if more specific patterns emerge.\n","\n","\n","3. **major_sports_event:**\n","\n","major sports events directly and negatively impacting the content viewership on the platform.\n","\n","Recommendations:\n","\n","\n","\n","*   Avoid Key Conflict Dates: Use a calendar of major sporting events (e.g., the Super Bowl, World Series, NBA Finals, World Cup) to inform your content release schedule. Do not launch major, high-budget, or highly anticipated content on a day with a major sports event.\n","\n","*   Highlight Short-Form Content: Use social media to promote short, snackable content that users can easily consume during commercial breaks or halftime.\n","\n","*   Social Media Engagement: Run campaigns that are relevant to the sports event but drive traffic back to your non-sports content. For example, a tweet might say, \"Need a break from the game? Here are 5 comedies to watch during halftime.\"\n","\n","*   Data-Driven Promotions: Use audience data to identify sports fans within your user base. Send them targeted push notifications or emails on sports event days, suggesting content that might appeal to them once the game is over.\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"YQSHwLZBL367"}}]}
